---
import Callout from '../../../../../components/Callout.astro';
import Code from '../../../../../components/Code.astro';
import SessionGrid from '../../../../../components/SessionGrid.astro';
import SessionPage from '../../../../../components/SessionPage.astro';
import SessionSection from '../../../../../components/SessionSection.astro';
import TagList from '../../../../../components/TagList.astro';

const tinyProgram = `var builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);

var app = builder.Build();

app.MapGet("/", () => new { ok = true });
app.MapGet("/status", () => new
{
    Service = "HelloApi",
    Status = "ok",
    CheckedAt = DateTimeOffset.UtcNow
});

app.Run();`;

const nodeAnalogy = `// Express-ish mental model, not ASP.NET code
const app = express();

// setup: register middleware/routes/services
app.get("/", (req, res) => res.json({ ok: true }));

// start listening
app.listen(3000);`;

const withServices = `var builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);

builder.Services.AddSingleton<AppInfo>();

var app = builder.Build();

app.MapGet("/status", (AppInfo info) => new
{
    info.Service,
    Status = "ok",
    CheckedAt = DateTimeOffset.UtcNow
});

app.Run();

public sealed class AppInfo
{
    public string Service { get; } = "HelloApi";
}`;

const endpointsExtension = `public static class EndpointRouteBuilderExtensions
{
    public static IEndpointRouteBuilder MapHelloEndpoints(
        this IEndpointRouteBuilder endpoints)
    {
        endpoints.MapGet("/", () => new { ok = true });

        endpoints.MapGet("/status", (AppInfo info) => new
        {
            info.Service,
            Status = "ok",
            CheckedAt = DateTimeOffset.UtcNow
        });

        return endpoints;
    }
}`;

const organizedProgram = `var builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);

builder.Services.AddSingleton<AppInfo>();

var app = builder.Build();

app.MapHelloEndpoints();

app.Run();`;

const servicesExtension = `public static class ServiceCollectionExtensions
{
    public static IServiceCollection AddHelloServices(
        this IServiceCollection services)
    {
        services.AddSingleton<AppInfo>();
        return services;
    }
}`;

const finalProgram = `var builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);

builder.Services.AddHelloServices();

var app = builder.Build();

app.MapHelloEndpoints();

app.Run();`;
---

<SessionPage
  title="Session 5 · Minimal API Program.cs structure"
  heading="Program.cs: builder, services, app, and extension methods"
  lede="Today’s win: read a Minimal API startup file without treating it as magic."
  backHref="/topics/dotnet/"
  backLabel=".NET sessions"
>
  <SessionSection title="Start from what you already learned">
    <p>
      You already noticed the important part: <code>app.MapHelloEndpoints()</code> looks like an instance method, but it can be an extension method. ASP.NET Core uses that pattern everywhere because startup code can grow quickly.
    </p>
    <Callout>
      Beginner rule: <code>Program.cs</code> is the app’s startup script. It builds the app, registers things the app can use, maps HTTP endpoints, then starts the server.
    </Callout>
  </SessionSection>

  <SessionSection title="The smallest useful shape">
    <Code code={tinyProgram} lang="csharp" />
    <p>Read it in four phases:</p>
    <ol>
      <li><code>builder</code>: collect configuration, logging, DI registrations, and hosting setup.</li>
      <li><code>builder.Services</code>: register objects the DI container may create later.</li>
      <li><code>app</code>: the built web application that can receive requests.</li>
      <li><code>app.Run()</code>: start the server loop.</li>
    </ol>
  </SessionSection>

  <SessionSection title="JS/Node analogy">
    <p>
      In Node/Express, one file often creates the app, registers routes/middleware, and starts listening. Minimal API <code>Program.cs</code> feels similar, but ASP.NET adds a formal builder phase before the app runs.
    </p>
    <Code code={nodeAnalogy} lang="js" />
    <SessionGrid>
      <div>
        <h3>Node-ish mental model</h3>
        <p>Create app, attach behavior, listen.</p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <h3>ASP.NET mental model</h3>
        <p>Create builder, register services/config, build app, map endpoints, run.</p>
      </div>
    </SessionGrid>
  </SessionSection>

  <SessionSection title="Reuse your DI model: services are registered before Build()">
    <p>
      You already know the core DI idea from the previous sessions. Here we are using it only to understand <code>Program.cs</code>: <code>builder.Services</code> is where you tell ASP.NET, “this object is available for handlers to ask for.”
    </p>
    <Code code={withServices} lang="csharp" />
    <p>
      The handler does not call <code>new AppInfo()</code>. It asks for <code>AppInfo info</code>, and the DI container provides it using the registration made during startup.
    </p>
  </SessionSection>

  <SessionSection title="Why move endpoint mapping into an extension method?">
    <p>
      If every route stays in <code>Program.cs</code>, the file slowly becomes a long scroll of unrelated setup. Extension methods let you keep the startup script readable without inventing a big framework.
    </p>
    <Code code={endpointsExtension} lang="csharp" />
    <Code code={organizedProgram} lang="csharp" />
    <TagList tags={['Program.cs stays high-level', 'routes can be grouped by feature', 'same runtime behavior', 'easier to scan']} />
    <Callout>
      This does not make routes special. It is still just calling methods during startup. The extension method is organization, not magic.
    </Callout>
  </SessionSection>

  <SessionSection title="Same pattern for services">
    <p>
      ASP.NET projects often use another extension method for registrations. The target type changes: endpoint mapping extends <code>IEndpointRouteBuilder</code>; service registration extends <code>IServiceCollection</code>.
    </p>
    <Code code={servicesExtension} lang="csharp" />
    <Code code={finalProgram} lang="csharp" />
    <p>
      Now <code>Program.cs</code> reads like a table of contents: add services, build app, map endpoints, run.
    </p>
  </SessionSection>

  <SessionSection title="Step-by-step request story">
    <ol>
      <li>The process starts and runs <code>Program.cs</code>.</li>
      <li><code>builder.Services.AddHelloServices()</code> registers <code>AppInfo</code>.</li>
      <li><code>builder.Build()</code> creates the <code>app</code> and its service provider.</li>
      <li><code>app.MapHelloEndpoints()</code> registers routes such as <code>/status</code>.</li>
      <li><code>app.Run()</code> starts accepting HTTP requests.</li>
      <li>When a request hits <code>/status</code>, ASP.NET calls the handler and provides <code>AppInfo</code>.</li>
    </ol>
  </SessionSection>

  <SessionSection title="Exercise — reply in Discord" variant="checkpoint">
    <p>Answer from memory. Short is good:</p>
    <ol>
      <li>In <code>var builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);</code>, what is the builder mainly for?</li>
      <li>Why do service registrations usually happen before <code>builder.Build()</code>?</li>
      <li>In <code>app.MapHelloEndpoints()</code>, what type is probably being extended?</li>
      <li>Rewrite this route name as a high-level extension-method call you might want in <code>Program.cs</code>: “map all order-related endpoints.”</li>
    </ol>
  </SessionSection>
</SessionPage>
